\par <h> <#/>}{\b\fs24\lang2057 Children of the lesser parents. <#/>'Luhya custom dictates that such children are a bad omen and destined to be outcasts.' </h>
\par <#/>}{\fs24\lang2057 Seven babies lay fast asleep in the cots neatly arranged in the spacious, clean room. <#/>Next to the babies was a larger cot and a weighing machine on top of a sideboard.
\par <#/>Several women chatted animatedly, one of them cuddling a baby. <#/>They all sat watching the sleeping babies.
\par <#/>To a stranger, the babies, aged between a few <-_day's><+_days> and two <-_month's><+_months> old, would be rightly there because after all the Kakamega Children's Home, like all others, takes care of children in difficult circumstances.
\par <#/>But the circumstances of the birth of these children were unique. <#/>They were not abandoned and left for death. <#/>Their mothers and relatives took them to the Home themselves.
\par <#/>Born in Kakamega District, the eight children are taboo children, born of incestuous relationships or between relatives.
\par <#/>The Luhya custom dictates that such children are abominable, a bad omen who are destined to be outcasts for as long as they live.
\par <#/>Such children have to be sent away immediately they are born to avoid the wrath of the gods "otherwise all the children in the family will die," a Kakamega elder says.
\par <#/>The children's wing of the Kakamega Children's Home, which was established about four years ago is a manifestation of the problem.
\par <#/>"Almost all the children we admit here are those born of such relationships," Mathias Wabwoba, the administrator of the home, says.
\par <#/>The eight children in the home and another one who was in hospital when we visited the home, had been brought by relatives or mothers soon after birth. <#/>They were all waiting to be adopted.
\par <#/>The home has a capacity for nine babies, and 25 older ones.
\par <#/>This year alone they have received 29 children, 23 of whom <-_are><+_were> born under these circumstances.
\par <#/>In 1989 the home had 46 children for adoption while in the previous year they had 29. <#/>"In actual fact 99 per cent of the children we admit here are those born between relatives," Wabwoba says.
\par <#/>"But because the community does not accept them, they ask us to take them for good."
\par Among the Maragoli, a sub-tribe of the Luhya, such children were traditionally left to die immediately they were born.
\par <#/>"Such a child would be placed on a rock in the sun and left to die," says Meshack Agoi, a senior chief, in Vihiga/Sabatia division.
\par <#/>"The parents of such a child would be sent away to another clan or to a neighbouring ethnic community, never to return to their home.
\par <#/>Rachel Musoga, a counsellor at the Family Planning Association of Kenya office, Kakamega, narrated a case in which a man in Isukha, Kakamega had a chi
ld with his daughter. <#/>The daughter went to live with the uncles but the man was forbidden <-_never><+_ever> to return home.
\par <#/>He returned years later, but died soon after. <#/>"Everybody believed he died because he disobeyed the rule of law," she says.
\par <#/>Chief Agoi explains that if such a child was let to live with relatives, all other children in the family could either die, become mad, lame or abnormal.
\par <#/>"But incestuous relationships were a rare occurrence then. <#/>It seems to be happening more often now, but because the law and Christianity forbids killing, some people are trying to deal with it quietly and in a more humane way," he says.
\par <#/>They do so by approaching the Children's home and the children's officer in Kakamega long before the children are born.
\par <#/>Others, mainly single girls dump the children at the Kakamega Hospital where they know they will be taken care of.
