\par }{\fs24\lang2057 She screamed. <#/>Villagers rushed to her house. <#/>And <-/>aaah, they grumbled as they returned to their homes.
\par <#/>What the villagers found to be an anti-climax was a matter of life and death to the woman. <#/>It was tearing her apart. <#/>Who was going to help her?
\par <#/>The woman was a widow. <#/>Her husband had died in a road accident a short while ago. <#/>In her particular community, a widow is considered to be a public property. <#/>Any man who knocks on
 her door should be opened for and actually entertained according to his wishes.
\par <#/>On that night, a man had forced his way into the house. <#/>The woman asked him to leave. <#/>He refused. <#/>He insisted on what he called "his right" because he was a man.
\par <#/>When he was at the point of raping her, she screamed. <#/>The villagers were surprised that she was screaming just because of a man. <#/>They would not help.- It was her problem and hers alone.
\par <#/>The incident was narrated to an attentive audience of church women leaders by Dr Sister Anne Nasimiyu, a lecturer at Kenyatta University recently at Sirikwa Hotel, Eldoret. <#/>She said it happened in her home area in western Kenya.
\par <#/>"If you become a widow and remain unmarried, you become public property," she said emotionally.
\par <#/>Dr Nasimiyu was reacting to a comment made by the Rev Jane Kamau of St Andrews Church, Nairobi. <#/>The Rev Jane had expressed shock as a result of what she found during a recent visit to Malawi.
\par <#/>"I was shocked to find that widows must remain dressed in black until they remarry," she said.
\par <#/>That is a form of intimidation to force women to remarry, she argued. <#/>The group was to learn of other absurd ways of forcing widows to remarry.
\par <#/>One woman gave an account of a widow who recently died. <#/>Nobody would bury her body arguing that she should have remarried. <#/>That, they argued, would have ensured her a decent burial.
\par <#/>"We the church women, joined our efforts together, and buried her," she said.
\par <#/>The church 
women leaders who had a three-day visit to Eldoret paid visits to two widows, Herma Muge, wife of the late Bishop Alexander Kipsang Muge and Rael Mutai, wife of the late general secretary of the reformed Churches of East Africa the late Rev Justin Mutai.

\par <#/>It was a time of expressing solidarity with the two women, giving them sympathy and what they called "a little consolation."
\par The women who hold leadership positions in their respective churches all over Kenya were led by the co-ordinator of the NCCK Women's desk, Julia Mulaha.
\par <#/>They explained that the consolation was little in that "no human being can be able to completely touch the aching heart and remove the pain left by a husband's death.
\par <#/>The Rev Jane who conducted a short, but touching sermon 
said the actual mourning for a widow starts at the funeral. <#/>Then all the mourners disperse to their respective homes and the woman experiences loneliness, a sense of despair and sees nothing to live for.
\par <#/>With or without realising this state of affairs, society is often quick to try and impose "traditional norms" on the widow as soon as possible.
\par <#/>Such traditional customs vary from one ethnic group to the next in Kenya. <#/>They sometimes vary from one section to the next in the same district. <#/
>Information compiled by Institute of African Studies of the University of Nairobi reveal interesting facts about various customs in certain districts.
\par <#/>Taking Baringo District, as an example, there are the Tugen, the Arror and the Ilchamus people. <#/>
When a Tugen woman is widowed, she is not supposed to be inherited by her husband's brothers or cousins. <#/>She is supposed to remain in her late husband's home.
\par <#/>She is free to continue bearing children with other men of her choice but who are not blood relatives of her late husband. <#/>Her chosen lovers are however, to be kept secret.
\par <#/>Like the women of Malawi, this woman is supposed to remove the beads around her neck, earrings and <-/armuletes> and replace them with others indicating widowhood. <#/>Such removal is known by three words <ea/>}{\i\fs24\lang2057 mosoget, }{
\fs24\lang2057 <ea/>}{\i\fs24\lang2057 mosoge or}{\fs24\lang2057 <ea/>}{\i\fs24\lang2057  mosok}{\fs24\lang2057 .
\par <#/>For the Arror, a widow's fate is mainly determined by the gender of her children. <#/>A widow who has at least one son need not go away when her husband dies. <#/>If she 
has only girls, she is given the option of remaining or going back to her parents.
\par <#/>If she remains, she is free to have children with any man in the village except her brother-in-law.
\par <#/>Unlike the Tugen, children born to her in this way do not belong to her late husband but to the biological fathers. <#/>Such fathers are expected to add resources to bring such children up.
\par <#/>The Ilchamus on the other hand give the widows an option of leaving or remaining. <#/>If she leaves and had no children, then the bride price has to be returned.
\par <#/>If she remains, she is instructed to select a man to father her children. <#/>The criteria here is that such a man must be of the same age group as her late husband and of the same lineage but not a brother-in-law.
\par <#/>In the case of Iteso people of Busia, the widow is "held" by one of the husband's brothers who becomes responsible for her and the children.
\par <#/>For the Masaai, widows can not legally marry but can cohabit with other men.
\par <#/>Custody of a Kamba widow, called <ea/>ndiwa, goes to the husband's full brother or cousin. <#/>This custodian is given the name of <ea/>}{\i\fs24\lang2057 musina}{\fs24\lang2057 . <#/>He is expected to live with the woman and manage the property }{
