\par }\pard\plain \s43\qj\nowidctlpar\adjustright \lang2057 {<#/>The floods took the residents of Ngorobani, Kirinyaga District, by surprise late one night last week destroying p
roperty worth thousands of shillings. <#/>NGUGI wa MBUGUA who visited the area soon after the disaster reports. 
\par }\pard\plain \qj\nowidctlpar\adjustright \fs20\lang1031 {\fs24\lang2057 <#/>Simon Njagi and his brother, Joseph Nyaga, float in their tiny hut every night. <#/>On the floor below their bed is a knee-high pool of sta
gnant water that has defied all attempts to remove it from the hut.
\par <#/>Njagi and Nyaga are victims of floods that rendered 200 families homeless in Kirinyaga District early last week.
\par <#/>The blitz was brought to bear on Kithogondo village in Mwea Division in the small hours of Sunday, May 19 after gods of the Thiba River went on the rampage bursting its banks.
\par <#/>Swelled by heavy rains in the Mt Kenya area, the wild waters of the Thiba, stormed into the village turning it into a temporary lake.
\par <#/>About 100 mud-walled and thatch-roofed huts were engulfed but the more than 1,000 occupants escaped unhurt. <#/>For a whole week, the displaced flood victims have been living with sympathetic neighbours.
\par <#/>But not so for the 24-year-old Njagi and his 20-year-old brother, Nyaga. <#/>"We cannot be accommodated by neighbours, they have no more room left," Njagi says.
\par <#/>It took only a few hours for the two to accept their harsh predicament and act the only way they knew how. <#/>At daybreak on Sunday, they came up with the `floating bed' idea.
\par <#/>Using strong nylon ropes, they fastened a bed on wooden beams in their tiny hut and suspended it over the water that has collected in the hut.
\par <#/>Every evening, Njagi and Nyaga wade through the murky and slow-moving flood to their hut, 50 metres from the shore. <#/>It takes a lot of dexterity and luck for them to evade erstwhile rubbish and latrine pits on their submerged path.
\par <#/>Once in the relative safety of the hut, the two brothers wade through more water as they struggle to ascend to their `hammock'.
\par <#/>"The nights are long and cold," says the stoic Njagi. <#/>"But it is better than sleeping out in the rain," Njagi says.
\par <#/>We visited the Kithogondo village on Friday afternoon. <#/>As we walked toward the southern end of the lake that was once home to more than 1,000 impoverished squatters, we were surprised to see Njagi walking through the quagmire.
\par <#/>The lone figure waded through the murky thigh-high water, his trousers hitched up to the waist perhaps risking some water-borne diseases.
\par <#/>Njagi is aware that the foundation of his two-month-old hut will soon give in to the pressure of the water surrounding. <#/>He is also aware that they could drown if the `air-borne' bed collapsed while they were asleep.
\par <#/>"We sleep in snatches. <#/>Any day now, I expect the hut to be swept away but do we have a choice?"
\par <#/>We were astonished by Njagi telling us that he had slept in the water-logged hut during the previous four days.
\par <#/>Njagi and Nyaga's experience is certainly a most touching one. <#/>Yet, as each victim, young and old, narrated their harrowing plight, the full import of their tragedy was brought home.
\par <#/>The adults among them have to forego food for the sake of their children some who attend local primary schools }{\v\fs24\lang2057 <&/>grammar}{\fs24\lang2057 . <#/>Many have not had a change of clothes since that Black Sunday as they salvaged none.

\par <#/>In the small hours of that Sunday morning, James Gitari was woken by a furious dance of <ea/>}{\i\fs24\lang2057 sufuria}{\fs24\lang2057 
. <#/>The vessels were floating on water that had collected on the floor and were bumping into each other with a loud metallic report.
\par <#/>Gitari then heard the blood-curdling screams. <#/>Terrified women, children and men panicked as the entire village was enveloped by the floods.
\par <#/>"I didn't try to salvage anything from the hut," says the 28-year-old Gitari. <#/>"All that mattered then was to escape with my life."
\par <#/>His hut, 10 metres from the dry zone, still has its door ajar. <#/>He never bothered to shut it as he scurried away, the steady flow of water slowing his progress.
\par <#/>Gitari's family was away on the night the floods set in. <#/>The man who earns a living as a temporary employee in the rice paddies, hopes that the floods will subside so that he can repair his hut and re-occupy it.
\par <#/>At around the same time cooking pots were performing their dance in Gitari's hut, Justa Muthoni Muruga stirred in her sleep.
\par <#/>It was 1 a.m. and the mother of nine, felt the urge to answer a call of nature. <#/>She did not get far for the moment she opened the door, a powerful gush of water rushed into the hut.
\par <#/>She forced her way out, stood on }{\b\v\fs24\lang2057 <&/>prep}{\fs24\lang2057  knee-high water and started screaming for help. <#/>Her children were sleeping in three other huts on the small unfenced compound.
\par <#/>"People from higher grounds where the flood had not reached came to our rescue but nothing was salvaged," Muruga says.
\par <#/>Her family lost seven chickens, six ducks and four goats. <#/>All utensils and clothes in the four huts were swept away. <#/>She estimates her loss at Sh20.000 including the mud-walled thatched huts.
\par <#/>The family is being accommodated by sympathetic families at a neighbouring village. <#/>"We sleep on the floor as there are no beds and live on rice and water," Muruga says with emotion.
\par <#/>During our visit, her eldest son, Wilberforce Maina, 22, and a brother had just returned from an unsuccessful fishing attempt at Karia, a tributary of the Thiba.
\par <#/>Like most other victims of the floods, Muruga winnows rice husks discarded in the locality by the Mwea Rice Mills, in the hope of salvaging leftover grains to feed her family.
\par <#/>Muruga, who settled at the now flooded village in 1986 says they have never experienced floods of such magnitude. <#/>Their only hope is for the Government or the Kirinyaga County Council to re-locate them to an alternative site, she says.
\par <X_>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 <#/>John Maina who moved to the village four months ago, says he lost six chickens and Sh200 in the flood.
\par <#/>Maina, whose hut is at the eastern end of the water-logged plot, recalls that he was woken up by loud screams on that fateful morning.
\par <#/>The 36-year-old casual worker had not moved his family to the village as he was yet to build a house. <#/>His wif
e and children live with his in-laws at Molo in Nakuru District. <#/>"Now, I have no illusion about them joining me here until a solution is found for us," he says.
\par <#/>While some feel that the 30-acre Kithogondo village can be reclaimed, some expressed their reluctance to settle there even if the water is drained. <#/>They said they have suffered enough and would hate to be there when the next floods come.
\par <#/>One of the victims, Bernard Njogu, suggested that the burst banks of the Thiba could be blocked and the Kithogondo village redeemed. <#/>But his argument was hotly contested by his colleagues.
\par <#/>Most of them seemed to agree that they have reached a point of no return. <#/>Either they vacate the village and settle elsewhere or suffer forever.
\par <#/>In the meantime, some are moving their families to live with relatives within and outside Kirinyaga District. <#/>Njogu's family, for instance, is living with his mother-in-law in another part of the district.
\par <#/>The Kithogondo village is near Ngurubani market in Wanguru town about 200 metres off the Nairobi-Embu road.
\par <#/>The flat area is in the rice\-growing Mwea zone. <#/>It is <-/succeptible> to floods due to its flatness.
\par <#/>The flood victims had built their huts on land belonging to the County Council after they were evicted from commercial plots at Wanguru town where they were squatters.
\par <#/>On Thursday, the Reverend Gitari of the CPK Kirinyaga diocese visited the victims and consoled them. <#/>He expressed fear over a possible outbreak of an epidemic due to the flooding, starvation and poor sanitation.
\par <#/>The local administration however assured the victims of the government's assistance.}{\fs24\lang2057 </X>
