\par <I> <h>}{\b\fs24\lang2057  }{\fs24\lang2057 <#/>}{\b\fs24\lang2057 International Women's Day supplement </h>
\par <h> <#/>How the fight for equality started }{\fs24\lang2057 </h>
\par <#/>Today, the world celebrates the 1990 edition of the International Women's Day.
\par <#/>It is an event that dates back to one of the very first women-instigated and implemented social and economic <-_revolution><+_revolutions>.
\par <#/>On March 8, 1857, a group of New York women garment workers held a demonstration  protesting their working conditions.
\par <#/>Exactly 51 years later - March 8, 1908 - a march was held in New York to commemorate that demonstration.
\par <#/>The International Women's Day was first proposed by Ms Clara Zetkin, a representative of the Socialist Women's Conference in Copenhagen, Denmark.
\par <#/>Europe was then on the verge of the First World War.
\par <#/>The colonial empires in Asia and Africa were feeling the first stirrings of nationalist revolt.
\par <#/>In North America, the movement for women's suffrage was questioning some of the basic assumptions of human relations.
\par <#/>Ms Zetkin's call to women to link their fight for equal rights with the fight to preserve international peace, struck a responsive chord.
\par <#/>The women's day was celebrated as a formal event for the first time in 1911 with more than a million women participating publicly.
\par <#/>in addition to the right to vote and to hold public office, they demanded the right to work, to vocational training and for an end to discrimination on the job.
\par <#/>Since that time, the significance of the event has grown and now has taken on a truly global character.
\par <#/>In Kenya, the International Women's Day was first observed on March 8, 1988. <#/>It was again celebrated last year.
\par <#/>In many countries of the world, it has become an occasion to review the progress women have made in their struggle for peace, equal rights and social progress.
\par <#/>In 1977, the General Assembly of the United Nations Organisation invited each country to proclaim, in accordance with their historical and national traditions and customs, any day of the year as United Nations Day for Women's Rights and International 
Peace.
\par <#/>Many countries of the world observe the International Women's Day on March 8.
\par <#/>The theme of the 1990 edition is progress for women is progress for all.
\par <#/>As Kenyans alongside the other international communities mark this important annual event, several organisations and leading women and political personalities have sent their greetings and messages of goodwill to women the world over:
\par Mr James Njiru, the Minister for Culture and Social Services says:
\par "It is recognised by the leadership of President Moi that women's role in national development is crucial and that development plans cannot be effectively implemented if the role is ignored."
\par <#/>Mrs F.R.B. Oeri is the head of the Women's bureau in collaboration with women non-governmental organisations "will continue to foster and intensify programmes and activities which are of interest" to Kenyan women }{\v <&/>grammar}{\fs24\lang2057 .

\par <#/>She wishes Kenyan women "fruitful celebrations, a prosperous year and successful development programmes."
\par <#/>A message from the African Women's Development and Communication Network (Femnet) office describes the International Women's day as an important occasion for African women.
\par <#/>A prominent Kenyan woman lawyer, Ms Lilian Mwaura, has sent messages in her capacity as chairman of the National Council of Women of Kenya (NCWK) and the Kenya chapter of International Federation of Women Lawyers (FIDA).
\par <#/>In one of her bulletins, Ms Mwaura says: "The future of women in Kenya seems brighter and it is our hope that there will be development in areas of law, customs and politics all aimed at improving the status of women."
\par <#/>Mrs Phoebe Asiyo is the good-will ambassador to the United Nations Development Fund for Women.
\par <#/>Mrs Asiyo wishes Kenyan women "good health and strength to forge ahead with our critical and central roles in the socio-economic development of our country."
\par <#/>The Swedish International Development Agency (SIDA), United Nations Development Programme (UNDP) and several other organisations too, have a message for Kenyan women.
\par }\pard\plain \s43\qj\nowidctlpar\adjustright \lang2057 {<#/>In its message, SIDA has pledged to continue supporting the women of Kenya, directly or indirectly through educational and health programmes, in water projects and soil conservation efforts.

\par <#/>In her statement to local womenfolk, Mrs Beth Mugo the national chairman of the Kenya Business and Professional Women's Club describes today's occasion as "yet another milestone in the struggle for equality and development.
