\par <I> <h>}{\b\fs24\lang2057  }{\fs24\lang2057 <#/>}{\b\fs24\lang2057 Building castles on shaky ground </h>
\par <h> <#/>Millions invested on plots without title deeds }{\fs24\lang2057 </h>}{\b\fs24\lang2057 
\par }{\fs24\lang2057 Simon Mwenjera knows only too well that a million shillings do not grow on trees. <#/>He is also aware that it is not glamorous to continue paying rent in a middle-class estate in Nairobi after you have built a home fit for a king.
\par <#/>Mwenjera, a city businessman cannot settle on a plot he developed at a cost of one million shillings a year ago.
\par <#/>The four-bedroom bungalow on the half-acre plot, eight kilometres from the city centre, is just the stuff the average Kenyan's dreams of a home are made of.
\par }\pard\plain \s43\qj\nowidctlpar\adjustright \lang2057 {<#/>And so why is Mwenjera reluctant to occupy the beautiful house? <#/>Could it be that on completion, the house was invaded by ghosts that now haunt it? <#/>The answer is no!
\par }\pard\plain \qj\nowidctlpar\adjustright \fs20\lang1031 {\fs24\lang2057 
<#/>Mwenjera is one of about 20 people who have built or are building country houses on the Thome Farm near Ruaraka. <#/>He is a pioneer having been the first to put up a dwelling house at a section of the large farm called Thome Five.
\par <#/>But like all plot owners in this Number Five, Mwenjera has nothing much he can show to prove ownership of the plot. <#/>He paid Shl00,000 for the plot in 1987 but has not got a title deed.
\par <#/>Being a "virgin" residential area, the Thome Farm has no infrastructural services such as water, electricity and roads.
\par <#/>The Nairobi City Commission is supposed to have provided these services but won't. <#/>It is said that the original shareholders of the Thome Farm owe the Commission nearly Sh200,000 in accumulated rates.
\par <#/>Mwenjera believes that these outstanding rates are the reason why plot owners cannot get title deeds. <#/>The Commissioner of Lands has to get a nod from the city fathers to release the deeds.
\par <#/>But due to the money said to be owed to it, the City Commission's nod is not forthcoming. <#/>At the centre of this stalemate are the Mwenjeras of Thome - home developers who desperately need the security of a title deed.
\par <#/>Mwenjera confesses: "We are building these houses without the City Commission approving our plans."
\par <#/>The Commission will not approve building plans for the Thome Five scheme until the reportedly outstanding rates are settled.
\par <#/>Real tragedy, says Mwenjera, is should the Commission decide to demolish their mansions. <#/>"God forbid, for we would hardly have any legal way of stopping the demolition."
\par <#/>The Thome Farm is an offshoot of Thome Farmers Company Limited which was incorporated as a private firm on June 29, 1972.
\par <#/>Records in the Registrar of Companies office indicate that the company was converted into a public entity on December 6, 1974. <#/>Its name changed to Thome Farmers Company (No.1) Limited on May 21, 1976. <#/>At its advent, it had 12 directors.
\par <#/>One of them, Simon Muchomba, was reluctant to discuss the issue of title deeds when contacted on Monday. <#/>He retorted in Kikuyu: "<ea_><X_>}{\i\v\fs24\lang2057 Tutirenda uteti na uhoro wa magatheti}{\i\fs24\lang2057 </X><ea/>}{\fs24\lang2057 
 (we don't want to be involved in politics and newspaper business)."
\par <#/>Muchomba, a retired teacher, was appointed secretary of the defunct Thome Farmers Company Limited on June 29, 1972.
\par <#/>Informed that a number of plot owners had complained about the company's failure to issue them title deeds, Muchomba said: "Some of those complaining are not shareholders. <#/>They are liars."
\par <#/>Mwenjera admits that most of the plot owners in the Thome Five scheme are not among the original shareholders. <#/>"After waiting for their title deeds in vain, about 90 per cent of the shareholders despaired and decided to sell their plots," he says.

\par <#/>To prove his point, Mwenjera produced a share certificate for Sh8,550 allotting him plot number 178 on the Thome Five scheme. <#/>"I bought the plot from a shareholder through a real estate agency," he adds.
\par <#/>The certificate, on an official letterhead of Thome, gives the name of a senior Cabinet Minister as the farmers' company adviser.
\par <#/>Some of the plot owners - not original shareholders - have been waiting for their title deeds for as long as 10 years. <#/>They say they have been calling or visiting Githunguri town where the Thome office is but to no avail.
\par <#/>"It has always been the same old story - that the title deeds are being processed," Mwenjera says.
\par <#/>A Presidential directive last year that all land-buying companies sub-divide land and issue title deeds by December 31, gave a ray of hope to the plot owners.
\par <#/>Mwenjera says that a `Mrs Kamau' of the Githunguri office assured him that the company would beat the Presidential directive.
\par <#/>That the "processing" of the deeds still drags on seven months from the expiry of the deadline, baffles him.
\par <#/>He has begun suspecting that some influential politician may have something to do with the company director's audacity in turning their backs to the deadline.
\par <#/>"He must be an absolutely powerful man," Mwenjera says of the politician. <#/>Last Friday, we called the Githunguri office where a woman employee said: "The matter of title deeds is with our advocates, Njoroge and Nyagah."
\par <#/>Asked about the roads, electricity and water, the women said without elaborating: "I heard the Minister saying that he is looking into that."
\par <#/>A lawyer at the Njoroge and Nyagah Advocates says they will hopefully "do the title deeds this year."
\par <#/>On the issue of accumulated City Commission rates, the lawyer says: "There is always a problem with urban plots. <#/>If rates are not paid regularly, they accumulate."
\par <#/>Mwenjera is not alone in the Thome dilemma. <#/>Although the City Commission will not approve building plans a lot of construction work is going on }{\b\v\fs24\lang2057 <+_on>}{\v\fs24\lang2057  }{\fs24\lang2057 the half-acre plots.
\par }\pard\plain \s43\qj\nowidctlpar\adjustright \lang2057 {<#/>Two of the most magnificent houses are being developed by a Nairobi obstestrician-gynaecologist, Dr Philomen Kiwool, and Stephen Ndichu who works for the Regional Centre for Remote Sensing.

\par }\pard\plain \qj\nowidctlpar\adjustright \fs20\lang1031 {<#/>}{\fs24\lang2057 Dr Kiwool says he bought his plot last November and has since been waiting for a title deed. <#/>His}{\i\fs24\lang2057  }{\fs24\lang2057 
five-bedroom bungalow, about 200 metres from the Garden Estate Road is nearing completion.
\par <#/>Ndichu, who is building a stately double-storied house says of the title deeds: "We don't know what is happening. <#/>We have been kept in the dark."
\par <#/>He bought his plot in 1987 and like all others paid Sh650 to the Thome Company for the provision of roads, water and a sewerage system.
\par <#/>That was over three years back. <#/>The 2,000 or so acre Thome Five, is a large expanse of overgrown bushes with beautiful isolated houses seemingly trapped in the mess.
\par <#/>Anyone wanting to develop their plot has to cut a temporary road through the bush. <#/>A case in point is Mwenjera who says he spent Sh7,000 on a 300-metre dry-weather road. <#/>"Previously, I would drive over other people's plots," he adds.
\par <#/>Recently, the 
Kenya Power and Lighting Company gave him a Sh188,000 quotation for power supply. <#/>The bill would be smaller if shared among the home developers. <#/>Regarding the money the farm shareholders owe the City Commission as rates, Mwenjera is of the opinion
 that the plot owners could contribute if it will resolve the stalemate.
\par <#/>It would appear that the Thome Farmers Company (No. 1) Limited has been at perpetual loggerheads with the Commission over outstanding rates.
\par <#/>Records at the Registrar of Companies office indicate that way back in 1988, the company had defaulted on Sh250,000 rates.
\par <#/>At an extraordinary meeting held at the Marige's chief office in Githunguri on April 30 of that year, the company's vice-chairman, John Bosco Kanyua Njuguna, raised the matter.
\par <#/>The meeting had been called to "review points" which would enable the directors }{\b\v\fs24\lang2057 <+_to>}{\fs24\lang2057  issue title deeds as soon as possible.
\par <#/>Says a long-winded minute of the meeting:
\par }\pard\plain \s43\qj\nowidctlpar\adjustright \lang2057 {"A few members of the company have not paid their dues and for that
 reason, the company is unable to pay the City Commission rates to enable (it) clear the company to the Commissioner of Lands so that the Commissioner would issue title deeds."
\par <X_>}{\v <#/>It was resolved that the Thome Company borrow Sh250,000 from a bank to clear the debt. <#/>The loan and interest accruing would be passed down to defaulting members.
\par }\pard\plain \qj\nowidctlpar\adjustright \fs20\lang1031 {\v\fs24\lang2057 <#/>The Thome farm plots for which title deeds have not been issued is on what is referred to as Thome Five.
\par <#/>Thome Farmers Company (No.1) Limited, Two, Three and Four are all registered but a search at the Registrar's revealed nothing about the controversial Thome Five. <#/>Apparently, it is not registered.
\par <#/>But plot owners told the }{\i\v\fs24\lang2057 Nation}{\v\fs24\lang2057  that the Thome Five plots are part of the assets of the Thome One, which once had 1,000 members.
\par <#/>Article Four in the company's `Memorandum of Association',
\par partly states the following as one of the objects for which it was established.
\par <#/>}{\i\v\fs24\lang2057 To construct, erect, and maintain either by the company or other parties, sewers, roads, streets and all other works, buildings, houses, flats, shops and other works of any description whatsoever, either upon the land acquired ...

\par <#/>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 Not much appears to have been done in pursuance of that article. <#/>At least as far as the Thome Five plots are concerned.
\par <#/>The Thome Farmers Company (No.1) Limited, is the founder company of No.2, Three and Four.
\par <#/>At its incorporation in 1972, it had a share capital of Sh60,000 which was divided into 3,000 shares of Sh20 each. <#/>The nominal share capital was raised to Sh1.94 million in March, 1977.
\par <#/>Way back in June 1976, the Registrar of Companies filed a criminal suit against the company and its directors for failing to deliver its annual returns for the previous two years.
\par <#/>Only the directors can tell whether the past misadventures of the parent company (Thome One) have anything to do with the present woes of the plot owners of Thome Five.
\par <#/>In the meantime, the Mwenjeras of Thome Five will have to view their spectacular mansions as a dream so close and yet so far. <#/>The castles they have spent so much money in }{\b\v\fs24\lang2057 <&/>prep}{\v\fs24\lang2057 
