\par <h> <#/>Kenya's Sixth Parliament has entered its fourth session }{\fs24\lang2057 </h>}{\b\fs24\lang2057 
\par }{\fs24\lang2057 <#/>Kenya's Sixth Parliament has entered its fourth session. <#/>Most people ask what these words mean. <#/>It simply <-_mean><+_means> that since independence six parliaments have been elected. <#/>And every time the President <-/proro
gues> Parliament, at the end of the year, that is, he effectively brings to an end that current session.
\par <#/>And under the powers conferred upon him under the constitution, the President at his own pleasure reconvenes Parliament through the proclamation in
 the Kenya gazette. <#/>This becomes a new session of parliament, whose opening is the colourful and significant State opening, again by the President.
\par <#/>The new session was officially opened by the President on Tuesday. <#/>The exposition of public poli
cy contained in the Presidential address delivered from the chair, is such an important matter, that it forms the basis of debate in the House for the next seven days uninterrupted. <#/>But before coming to that, it is important to highlight some of the P
resident's remarks as contained in the address.
\par <#/>During this address the President touched on several matters of public policy as well as national and international matters, and hinted to the members some of the government bills and papers that would be 
tabled before the house in the current sitting. <#/>In a no nonsense tone, the President said all and sundry must obey laws passed by Parliament.
\par <#/>He said whereas most people can debate on the merits of this or that law, it is no excuse to fail to stric
tly adhere to all the laws of the land passed by Parliament. <#/>And he assured members that the government will protect the dignity of the House, by ensuring that laws passed by the  National Assembly are followed to the letter. <#/>It is in the interest
 of Kenyan society, that the idea of a multi-party system be shelved until such a time the society is cohesive enough, said the President.
\par <#/>The next business of the house during a new session is to appoint members of the important sessional committee. <#
/>This is the committee charged with the responsibility of drawing up the business of the House for the rest of the session which ends with the Christmas recess. <#/>The first day is normally dominated by procedural motions, making it a hectic time for th
e leader of government business. <#/>In his absence his deputy holds fast.
\par }\pard\plain \s43\qj\nowidctlpar\adjustright \lang2057 {<X_>}{\v <#/>And since the Vice-President and Minister for Finance Professor George Saitoti is currently away, it was his able deputy, Mr Nicholas Biwott, who steered the business of the 
House until all the procedural motions went through, to the cheering and applause of all the members.
\par }\pard\plain \qj\nowidctlpar\adjustright \fs20\lang1031 {\v <#/>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 When Parliament was on the December recess, two bye-elections were held in Kangundo and Ndhiwa. <#/>The new representatives were sworn by the deputy s
peaker, Mr Kalonzo Musyoka. <#/>Mr Joseph Kimeu Ngutu, a former commandant of police training college, Kiganjo replaced veteran Paul Ngei, while a former member for Ndhiwa regained his seat replacing the late Ochola MakAnyengo.
\par <#/>Parliament also mourned 
three departed <-/colleaques>, Dr Richard Koech, (Kipkelion), Dr Robert Tanui (Mosop) and Mr Meshack ole Nampaso (Narok South). <#/>President Moi led members in observing a minute's silence in memory of the three departed legislators. <#/>On behalf of all
 the members, the Speaker, Mr Moses Kiprono arap Keino sent a message of <-_condolences><+_condolence> to the families and constituents of the bereaved.
\par <#/>The house then approved names of 20 members who will constitute the sessional committee, which went 
into session immediately to draw up the business of the House. <#/>There was <-_no><+_not> much debate on these members, although some felt that the committee should be made up of new members, not similar to the last session.
\par <#/>Mr Biwott assured the memb
ers that the familiar names were only repeated merely for continuity purposes. <#/>Otherwise every effort is made to ensure as many new members of the committee as possible are selected in order to give them not just the opportunity to serve, but also ena
ble them }{\b\v\fs24\lang2057 <+_to>}{\v\fs24\lang2057  gain experience.
\par <#/>When Mr Biwott then moved the motion on the exposition of public policy contained in the President's address, he opened deliberations of the House and set the tune for the next seven days. <#/>He strongly hit at proponen
ts of multi parties and those disgruntled elements geared towards causing disunity in Kenya. <#/>In their contributions, the members attacked an unnamed ambassador who was accused of travelling to the countryside and distributing books.}{\fs24\lang2057 
</X>
